{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778467453428,"sessionID":"ses_1eb17ff60ffeOJ9MpRqtcvbz5Z","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"functions.write:33","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/runner/work/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","content":"# Research for NTR: p24 cargo receptor complex (GO-ontology issue #31295)\n\n## Summary\n\nThe p24 cargo receptor complex is a conserved hetero-oligomeric protein complex that localizes to endoplasmic reticulum (ER) exit sites and functions as a cargo receptor for COPII-mediated anterograde transport from the ER to the Golgi apparatus. It is especially important for the selective transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI)-anchored proteins. The complex is typically tetrameric, containing one member from each of the four p24 subfamilies (alpha, beta, gamma, delta). The complex cycles continuously between the ER and Golgi compartments, and is itself returned to the ER via COPI retrograde vesicles.\n\n## Validated References\n\n### PMID:32456004 \"Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum.\"\n* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 complex is a conserved hetero-oligomeric complex that functions as a cargo receptor for COPII vesicles.\"\n    - The p24 complex localizes to ER exit sites.\n    - It functions in the selective export of secretory cargo from the ER.\n\n### PMID:34647572 \"Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1.\"\n* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"p24 family members function as cargo receptors for GPI-anchored proteins.\"\n    - Specific p24 family members act as cargo receptors.\n    - Demonstrates differential usage of p24 members for different cargo types.\n\n### PMID:27569046 \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport.\"\n* SUPPORT: PMID:27569046 \"p24 proteins form hetero-oligomeric complexes important for cargo transport.\"\n    - Structural basis of p24 complex formation.\n    - p24β and p24δ domains interact in complex formation.\n\n### PMID:19566487 \"The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface.\"\n* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"p24 proteins are involved in selective transport at the ER-Golgi interface.\"\n    - p24 proteins cycle between ER and Golgi.\n    - They are involved in selective cargo transport.\n\n### PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins: key players in the regulation of trafficking along the secretory pathway.\"\n* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins regulate trafficking along the secretory pathway.\"\n    - p24 proteins are key regulators of secretory pathway trafficking.\n    - They are cargo receptors for COPII vesicles.\n\n## Additional Notes\n\n- In S. pombe, p24 family members include Erp5, Emp24, Erp2, and Erv25.\n- In humans, orthologs are TMED4/TMED9, TMED2, TMED3, and TMED10 respectively.\n- The complex is commonly referred to as the \"p24 complex\" in the literature.\n- The complex has a dual role: anterograde cargo selection into COPII vesicles, and involvement in retrograde COPI vesicle formation for its own recycling.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/runner/work/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"RESEARCH.md","time":{"start":1778467453419,"end":1778467453426}},"id":"prt_e14eb9aac001abPT7tuVTtVayv","sessionID":"ses_1eb17ff60ffeOJ9MpRqtcvbz5Z","messageID":"msg_e14eb0a690011kgx8nrbjMFLk3"}}
